{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492831"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:46:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:46:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1165"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1165"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.52,0.05,0.39,0.01,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1165"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81333"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1165"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1165"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66675"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"7982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7916"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8548"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27808"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42233"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81333","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81333"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of a rash on his arms. He has mild tenderness on palpation but no itch or other symptoms. He recently completed a course of penicillin five days ago for a throat infection. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 78/min, blood pressure 130/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.6\u00b0C. There are erythematous, palpable purpuric lesions on both arms (Image 1, 2). The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Erythema multiforme","Lupus erythematosus","Vasculitis","Psoriasis","Urticaria"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with palpable purpura following recent antibiotic use, which is characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Evasculitis\u003C/strong\u003E. The timing and appearance of the rash suggests hypersensitivity vasculitis, which typically develops 7-10 days after exposure to a triggering agent such as medications (particularly antibiotics) or infections. The presence of fever and the temporal relationship with penicillin use strongly support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErythema multiforme\u003C/strong\u003E presents with characteristic target lesions that have three distinct zones: a central dusky or blistering area, a pale pink oedematous zone, and an erythematous outer ring. While it can be triggered by medications, the morphology of the lesions in this case is not consistent with erythema multiforme.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELupus erythematosus\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a photosensitive malar rash, discoid lesions, or other cutaneous manifestations. The acute onset and relationship to medication make lupus unlikely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsoriasis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by well-demarcated erythematous plaques with silvery scale. The acute onset, lack of scale, and presence of purpura make psoriasis an unlikely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrticaria\u003C/strong\u003E presents as raised, erythematous, and pruritic wheals that are typically transient and resolve within 24 hours. The presence of palpable purpura and lack of pruritus make urticaria unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Cutaneous vasculitis commonly presents as palpable purpura and may be triggered by medications, particularly antibiotics.","Recent infection and medication use are important historical features in diagnosing hypersensitivity vasculitis.","Hypersensitivity vasculitis typically develops 7-10 days after exposure to the triggering agent."],"references":["Savage CO, Harper L, Cockwell P, Adu D, Howie AJ. ABC of arterial and vascular disease: vasculitis. BMJ. 2000 May 13;320(7245):1325-8."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66675"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1165"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19603"},{"type":"media","id":"19604"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19603"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cb647e72-382d-4c67-b686-c89bab1431f5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cb647e72-382d-4c67-b686-c89bab1431f5.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":538,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"19604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19604"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c99f3a8a-6554-4299-90c9-c28e407b4144.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c99f3a8a-6554-4299-90c9-c28e407b4144.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":239}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66675","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66675"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"